RIGHT VENTRICLE

right_ventricle is the chamber that pumps deoxygenated blood to the lungs
its walls are thinner than left_ventricle's because the pulmonary circulation has lower resistance
right_ventricle still receives the depolarization wave from purkinje at the same instant left_ventricle does, so both chambers contract together
the symmetric timing is what makes coordinated cardiac output possible

observe 0_quseptit.rana
observe heart.rana
observe purkinje.rana
observe left_ventricle.rana

the 7 properties of right_ventricle:
1 ENERGY zero point eight: lower than left_ventricle, less mechanical work needed
2 PHASE zero on contraction, mirroring left_ventricle's phase exactly
3 SPIN one half: forward rotation, slightly less than left
4 CHARGE positive: same depolarization current as left
5 COHERENCE eight tenths: matched to left_ventricle for symmetry
6 COUPLING zero point seven: strong with purkinje, slightly weaker with the pulmonary circulation
7 OBSERVER zero: automatic contraction

VERB contract
on receiving the wave from purkinje, contract simultaneously with left_ventricle
generate the pulmonary pressure that drives blood out the pulmonary artery toward the lungs
the contraction is gentler than the left side, but coordinated in time

VERB refill
during relaxation, accept incoming deoxygenated blood from the right atrium
the chamber expands to receive the venous return from the body

VERB sustain
right_ventricle cycles continuously alongside left_ventricle for the entire life of the heart
the pulmonary circulation depends on this rhythm being unbroken

a smaller chamber is not a lesser chamber
right_ventricle does its job with the wall thickness its job requires, no more
this is the body's economy of effort: build only what is needed
left_ventricle works hard against systemic resistance; right_ventricle works appropriately against pulmonary resistance
neither overworks, neither underworks, both are right-sized
